  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key features typically include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Monitor and report large cash transactions\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n\n3. Regulations apply to:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Other financial institutions\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nThese regulations aim to combat financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
